sec.p:
The family
Chromadoridae Filipjev, 1917 (Nematoda, Chromadorida ,), is distributed worldwide and is often among the most abundant in deep-sea environments (
Lambshead et al . 2003
;
Ramirez-Llodra et al. 2010
;
Muthumbi et al . 2011
).
Spilipherinae Filipjev, 1918 is one of the five subfamilies of Chromadoridae , characterized by possessing a buccal cavity with three or more teeth, spiral amphidial fovea (cryptospiral with a circular outline or a single-loop spiral with a maximum of 1.5 turns), pharynx with subdivided basal bulb, precloacal supplements setose or absent, tail conical or elongated ( Decraemer & Smol 2006 ; Tchesunov 2014 ).

The genus 
AcantholaimusAllgén, 1933
is the most diverse of the subfamily 

Spilipherinae 
Filipjev, 1918
and it is considered one of the most typical deep-sea genera (
Tietjen 1989
; 
Soetaert & Heip 1995
; 
Muthumbi & Vincx 1997
; 
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016a
; 
Lins et al., 2018
). This genus was erected on the basis of 
five specimens
obtained from samples collected in the Trondheim fjord (
Norway
) and initially placed in 

Axonolaimidae 
Filipjev, 1918
(
Allgén 1933
; 
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016a
). However, its taxonomic position has changed several times since it was established (
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016a
; 
Manoel et al. 2017
; 
Venekey et al. 2019
). Recently, 
Miljutin and Miljutina (2016a)
performed a review summarizing all available information on the morphology, taxonomy, distribution, ecology and biology of the genus.

The main diagnostic characteristics of 
Acantholaimus
include the punctate cuticle; large round amphidial fovea, with interrupted posterior rim or nearly comma-shaped (spiral in one species) and buccal cavity armed with three or more solid teeth (small or large), often eversible (
Venekey et al. 2019
). The shape of the male spicules is unique, broad and funnel-shaped proximally, thin distally, with a mid-section comprising a curved triangular plate with a complicated system of cuticular thickenings. The associated gubernaculum is usually a simple structure, blade- or rod-shaped with a bifurcated distal end (
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016a
). The most notable characteristic of 
Acantholaimus
is its huge spermatozoa which are considered to be among the largest known in the phylum Nematoda, including the large parasitic species (
Bird & Bird 1991
; 
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016b
).

Species of 
Acantholaimus
have been found in all oceans (
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016a
; 
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016b
). Several species have been reported to occur in two or three oceans and may be formally considered as cosmopolitan (
Miljutina et al. 2010
). Among the 44 species considered valid to the genus, only five species have been described for shallow waters (
A. calathusGerlach, Schrage & Riemann, 1979
; 
A. longisetosusAllgén, 1933
; 
A. marliaeManoel, Silva & Esteves, 2017
; 
A. polydentatusGerlach, 1951
and 
A. quadridentatusJensen, 1985
). Of the deep-sea species, most of them were reported at depths> 
2000 m
(
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016a
), with the deepest samples collected from a trench at a depth of 
8380 m
(
Tietjen 1989
).

Presumably, the propensity of Acantholaimids to inhabit the deep sea may be explained by their apparent specificity for fine, muddy sediments. As a rule, they are not reported in sandy sediments (
Miljutin & Miljutina 2016a
). This genus is suggested to follow a semi-sessile life strategy, using its long filiform tail as an anchor in fine sand and muddy sediments (
Riemann 1974
). This life strategy may also enable animals to move throughout the very narrow interstices of fine sediments (
Thistle & Sherman 1985
).

The Santos Basin extends from the states of Rio de Janeiro to Santa Catarina , with the northern margin defined by the Campos Basin, and the southern margin defined by the Pelotas Basin. The basin covers an area of approximately 352,000 km2 and reaches depths of 3,000 m (
Souza & Sgarbi 2019
).

Sampling was carried out in 2018 (from 25 July to 11 August) on the continental slope of the Santos Basin. Onboard the RV ‘Seward Johnson’, samples were taken with plastic corer (
10cm2
) inserted in a box corer.

In the laboratory, sediment samples were sieved using a 300 μm mesh followed by a 38 μm mesh sieve which was used to retain the meiobenthic organisms. The samples remaining in the 38 μm mesh were extracted with colloidal silica (
Somerfield et al. 2005
).

